ts of financial aid among poor rural college students at four universities in china while ascertaining impacts of a scholarship intervention through use of a randomized controlled research design first we identify the determinants of obtaining financial aid within the control group by using probit and ols analysis we find that opportunities to obtain financial aid are only statistically correlated with gaokao score which is consistent with qualitative data from interviews of control group students furthermore using ols models with and without university fixed effects we test impacts of the scholarships on student self esteem and psychological well being time allocation and family outcomes such as debt burden none of the effects of the scholarship program are statistically significant and in fact the vast majority of students in the control group were able to obtain financial aid on their own whether through grants and scholarships or loans we find therefore that efforts to alleviate the financial burden of college on the poor have been relatively successful and that the most cost effective solutions to the education gap are likely through interventions that occur long before students reach college download pdf+ complete modified may 2011 pdf 226_ _financial_aid_4u_paper_ pdf 531.4 kb topics organizations china stanford university all rights reserved 650 723 2300 terms of use copyright complaints rss+ rss xml feeds
